data.reasoningText:
We have .NET 8 SDK (8.0.419 is latest). The issue might be that `global.json` is forcing a specific SDK or the default SDK is rolling forward to .NET 10. Let me check if the global.json is pinning an SDK version, and also check why the .NET 10 SDK is being used. Actually, the global.json has:

```json
{
  "test": {
    "runner": "VSTest"
  }
}
```

That doesn't pin an SDK, so it'll use the latest which is 10.0.201. And with .NET 10 SDK, when you have OutputType=Exe and net8.0-windows, it might try to resolve WindowsDesktop.App.


I could pin to .NET 8 in global.json or try building without OutputType=Exe to isolate the trigger, but looking closer at the issue—the .NET 10 SDK built the baseline fine initially, so the real culprit is likely one of the new packages introducing a FrameworkReference for WindowsDesktop.App. I'm suspecting StaFact 3.x or the Combinatorial package might be the source, so let me test removing those first.
